{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_evans_ver01/data/sn86063730/00332893762/1930090902/0145.xml":{"full_text":"SEVEN KILLED\nIN EXPLOSION\nLocomotive Blows Up In\nRound House YaVd;\n12 Injured\nPHILADELPHIA. Sept.\nSeven men were killed and a dozen\nothers were injured today In the\nexplosion of a pusher engine in\nthe round house yard of the Read\ning Railroad at Third street and\nErie avenue.\nThe engine was used In pushing\nheavy freight trains over grades.\nThe identified dead are:\nJohn Btemiller. roundhouse fore\nman; Fred C. Spangler, engineman:\nand John Kelley, engine inspector\nThe blast let loose a detonation\nthat was heard throughout the en\ntire neighborhood. For a few sec\nonds after the erplosion chunks of\nmetal fell like rain about the yards\nand employes scurried to shelter\nSome of the bodies were blown 15\nto 20 feet in the :dr and landed on\na nearby embankment.\nIt is the rule to Inspect all loco\nmotiv's each morning.\nThe pusher had been brought out\non the turn table and had been\ntaken off again but stopped about\n100 feet away. Spangler discovered\nsomething wrong with the injector\nand called the roundhouse foreman\nA numbe of other men gathered\nabout the engine and while the\nexamination was in progress the\nexplosion took place.\nWater Meeting Is\nPlanned Thursday\nA meeting to discuss the equit\nable distribution of waters of the\nRio Grande will be held at \u2666*ie loss.!\nchambers of commerce Thursday\nnight, it was announced today.\nW. E. Anderson. San Benito, fed\neral representative and engineer in\ncharge of the work, will be one of\nthe principal speakers on the pro\ngram. Frank Robertson, also of San\nBenito will be present representing\nwater interests.\nSeveral representatives of the\nValley chambers of commerce have\nbeen invited and have signified\ntheir intentions of being present,\nlocal officials explained.\nRaymondville Youth\nKilled in Accident\nRAYMONDVILLE. Sept. 9\u2014Ei\nwin Olover. 19 years of age was\nkilled Monday evening about 6 p.\nm. in a truck accident two miles\nNorth of Raymondville. Elwin with\nhis brother John were driving out\nof a field on the new Yturria high\nway and were scuffling. The truck\nhit a rut or some other obstruction\nand Elwin was thrown out on his\nhead. He war. rushed to the office\nof Dr. J. D. McCann but died with\nin fifteen minutes after arriving\nthere, never ha\\*ing regained cons\nciousness.\nHe was the son of J. D. Glover\nwho lives at the North edge of\nRaymondville. They came here\nabout a year ago from Oklahoma.\nThe funeral will be held Tuesday\nevening at 4 p. m.. from the home\nand burial will be in Eastlawn\nCemetery?\nCustoms Officials\nAwait Brew Report\nCustoms officers are holding up\nfiling charges on a San Benito\nwoman pending the analysis of\nhome brew in the federal laborat\nories at Port Worth.\nMounted Customs Officers Roy\nand James Collins raided the\nwoman's home Saturday evening\nbrew.\nand seized 266 bottles of home\nPolice Station Is\nBeing Remodelled\nThe Brownsville police station is,\nbeing remodelled. In the past, the\npolice desk was located in the open\nhall formerly occupied by the fire\nstation.\nOne half of the room is being\nconstructed into a room to be used\nas the police station. The rear half\nwill be used by the police cars.\nFormer Resident\nBrownsville Visitor\nWalter Guess. Dallas, arrived in\nBrownsville early this week with\nplans for an indefinite visit here.\nMr. Guess was a resident of\nBrownsville for several years, mov\ning to Dallas three years ago with\nhis family. He was unaccompanied\non his present visit.\nRAIL OFFICIAL DEAD\nCHICAGO. Sept. 9\u2014UP)\u2014Leonard\nA. Busby, 61, president of the Chi\ncago City Railway company and a\nleader in business affairs here for\nmany years, died todav.\nWhom Can You Name\nExecutor of your Estate?\nA FRIEND?\nHe may move away, or die, or become financially\nirresponsible.\nYOUR WIFE?\nShe must seek help. Whom would she rely upon?\nA RELATIVE?\nFew relatives are impartial.\nA BUSINESS ASSOCIATE?\nHe might be too closely identified with your in\nterests.\nA CORPORATE TRUSTEE?\nThe cost is no greater. You ally with your in\nterests the resources, responsibility, and per\nmanence of a reliable bank. This method is\nsure. Every other is makeshift.\n\nCOURAGE OF PEOPLE CURE\nOF BUSINESS DEPRESSION\nNEW YORK. Sept. 9.\u2014{jTt\u2014The\npresent business depression \u201ccan\nbe cured only by the courage and\nactivity of our people.\" said Rich\nard Whitney, president of the New\nYork stock exchange, in an address\ntoday before the Merchants' associa\ntion of New York City.\nTaking as his topic \u201ctrade depres\nsions and stock panics,\u201d Whitney\nasserted that the decline in security\nvalues last fall was not cause of\nthe business slump but that it was.\non the contrary, \u201cthe general real\nization of the downward trend in\ntrade conditions\" which initiated\nthe break in stocks.\n\u201cIf the stock market did not\ncause the trade depression,\u201d he\nadded, \u201cit is clear that the stock\nmarket cannot cure it. Many people\nstill seem to believe that rising\nsecurity prices will forecast the\nend of the present period in busi\nness. That may be so. but before\nsecurity prices rise there must be\nconfidence that business has turn\ned the comer.\n\u201cOur natural resources are as\ngreat today as they were last year\nOur great business organizations are\nin strong financial condition, and\nour Industrial plants are at the\nhighest state of efficient develop\nment. Credit is abundant. With the\nexception of the difficulties that\nhave arisen as a result of the\ndrastic deflation of commodity\nprices, the business horizon is clear\n\u201cWhat is needed, therefore, i\u00ab\ncourageous and intelligent effort\nand confidence in the future of our\ncountry. We all know that the pre\nsent period cannot long endure:\nyet. individually, many of use are\nhesitant and wish to wait until\nothers have had the courage tr\ntake the initiative. I am confident\nif the great organizations of busi\nness men throughout the country\nwill put their shoulders to the\nwheel, that the period of hesitation\nwill be measurablv shortened and\nthe reestablishment of prosperity lr\nthe United States will become ar\naccomplished fact.\"\nOver-produetion. Mr. Whitnev as\nserted, was the basic cause of the\ndepression and the breaking point\nwas reached last summer when the\nconsumption could no longer keep\npace with the enormous output of\nGoods. The most dramatic result\nof the unsettled equilibrium was\nthe stock market nanie.\nTODAY\u2019S MARKETS\u201d\nN. Y. STOCKS\nNEW YORK, Sept. 9\u2014(A*)\u2014Active\nbidding for the Tobacco shares,\nwhich rose one to five points, re\nvived buying of the general list in\nthe earlier hours of today's stock\nmarket after a demonstration of\nstrength, in the utilities and numer\nous specialties had shown signs of\nslackening.\nA representative list of stocks im\nproved one to two points. The short\ninterest in Gillette had an uneasy\ntime when the shares rallied from\n61 to nearly 65. Auburn Auto,\nwhich rallied 10 points yesterday,\nreacted on profit taking.\nCall money renewed at 2 1-2 per\ncent.\nThe close was steady. Sales ap\nproximated 1,650.000 shares.\nCOTTON STEADY\nNEW ORLEANS, Sept. 9.\u2014(An\u2014\ni Cotton was fairly steady today\nj with much lower than due Liver\nJ pool cables. First trades here show\ned losses of 3 to 4 points and Oct\nober soon traded down to 1&.79 and\nDecember to 10.96, or 5 to 7 points\nunder yesterday's close.\nThe market then rallied four\npoints under yesterday's close.\nThe market then rallied four\npoints on a little covering and at\ni the end of the first hour was steady\nand near the highs. Traders ap\ni peared to have recovered from the\nshock of yesterday's bearish cotton\nestimates.\nThe immediate selling stimulated\nby yesterday's government crop\nfigures appeared to have run its\nI course, and after the early decline\nprices were steadier on trade buy\ning and covering. There was very\nlittle southern selling in evidence\nafter the first half hour and while\nthe buying was by no means ag\ngressive, prices worked back to\nabout or a shade over yesterday\u2019s\nclosing quotations. At midday, act\nive months were 1 point lower to 3\nhigher with the new October selling\nat 10.86 and March at 11.31.\nNEW YORK COTTON\nNEW YORK, Sept. 9.\u2014(A5!\u2014Cat\nton opened steady at a decline of\n3 to 8 points under a renewal of\nyesterday\u2019s selling movement and\nin response to weakness in Liver\npool.\nThe decline brought in consider\nable trade buying and covering\nwhich caused bulges of a point or\ntwo right after the opening, but\nthe demand was supplied by fur\nther liquidation combined with\nsome Wall Street, local and south\ned selling. At the end of the first\nhalf hour, new October was selling\naround 10.77 and March 11.22, mak\ning net declines of about 6 to 10\npoints on the more active positions.\nCHICAGO GRAIN\nCHICAGO. Sept. 9\u2014(A**\u2014Scat\ntered commission house selling of\nwheat eased the market down here\ntoday in early trading. Commission\nhouses also sold com and this\ncaused a decline to below yester\nday\u2019s finish.\nOpening l-4f?3-4c lower, wheat\nslipped downgrade still more, but i\nrallied slightly and held around\nsteady Just below the opening lev\nels. Corn started unchanged to j\n1 l-4c lower, sank under selling,\nand then steadied.\nK. C. LIVESTOCK\nKANSAS CITY. Sept. 9.\u2014W\u2014\n\u00abU. S. D. A.l\u2014Hogs 6500: steady to\n10 cents higher: top 10.80: packing\nSOWS 8.00-9 25: Stock pigs 7.5&-8.40.\nCattle: 8,000; calves 2.000; kill\ning classes steady to 25 higher.\nStockers and feeders fully steady.\nSteers, good and <(.ioice 600-900\nlbs. 9.75 to 12.35; 900-1500 lbs. 9.25\n12.35; common and medium 600 lbs\nup 5.25-9.25; heifers, good and\nchoice 550-850 lbs. 9.25-12 00; cows,\ngood and choice 5.25-7.25; vealers\nimilkfed) medium to choice 6.00\n10.00; stocker and feeder steers,\ngood and choice, 6.508.75.\nSheep 10,000; lambs generally\nsteady; sheep, weak to 25 lower,\nLambs, good and choice 900 lbs.\ndown 7.50-8.25; ewes; medium to\nchoice 150 lbs. down 2 00-3.75.\nFeeder lambs, good and choice 50\n75 lbs. 5.75-6.50.\nBITTER AND EGGS\nCHICAGO. Sept. 9 A*;\u2014Butter\neasy; creamery extras. 38; stand\nards. 37 1-2; extra firsts. 37*137 1-2;\nfirsts 3515 36 1-2; seconds. 33^34.\nEggs: easy; extra firsts. 28 1-2;\nfresh graded firsts. 27; fresh c r\nrent receipts 25-26; ordinary cur\nrent receipts 16^ 23.\nSPEAKER\n(Continued from page 1)\nof Chambers county, had organized\nthe first company of confederate\nsoldiers to follow the flag of Let\nand Johnson throughout four vearr\nof bitter conflict between the\nstates.\u201d\nHe described Sterling In the run\noff as \u201chead erect and shoulderr\nsquare, with an open countenance\na clear conscience and an honor\nable past; a man born almost Ir\nabject poverty, who had suffered\nthe trials and tribulations of the\npoor.\nRailways Approve\nVegetable Rates\n(Special to The Herald.i\nSAN BENITO. Sept. 9\u2014C. E j\nFleming, industrial traffic man\nager. has received a letter stating\nthat the executive committee o\nthe central freight association ha:\napproved the new mixed vegetable\nrates of the southwest on freight\ninto territory east of Chicago and\nnorth of the Ohio River.\nAn immediate concurrence will be\ncertain to follow In the territory\neast of the* Mississippi and south\nof the Ohio river to the Atlantic\ncoast, the letter stated.\nRailroads in the association have\nrequested immediate publication o'\nthe new regulations that they may j\ntake effect by the opening of thV\nshipping season.\nThe reduced basis will mean r\nsaving of approximately $60 per\ncar. It was stated.\nThe letter came from the Kroger\nGrocery and baking company of\nCincinnati, which has been co\noperating with the Valley in secur-\ninp the new rates.\nI---\u00ab\nThe Funniest\nHit on Earth!\n\"The Cocoanuts\u201d was\njust a starter. The boys\nsaved their wildest mo\nments, their wisest\ncracks, their most dev\nastating hilarity for\nTheir second screen\nscream\u2014\u201cAnimal\nCrackers\u201d\nLast Times Today\n\u201cDIXIANA\u201d\nwith\nBEBE DANIELS\nBert Wheeler\nRobert W\u2019oolsey\nI\nDIVER BURIED\nUNDER WATER\n\nNEW ORLEANS. Sept. 9\u2014</P)\u2014I\nNick A Danese, 60. veteran diver,\nwas imprisoned under water today\nwhile scores of men, including four\nother divers, sought to free him\nfrom pilings against which a tre\nmendous pressure of water from\nLake Pontehartram swept him yes- j\nterday noon.\nIntermittent jerks on an air hose\ntold rescue workers that lie still\nwas alive.\nTwo hundred negroes worked last\nnight, aided by searchlights, to\nbuild a dam to divert water from\nthe lake and release the pressure\nthat gripped the diver.\nDanese was caught while trying\nto stop a leak under pumping sta\ntion No. 2 of the Jefferson Drain\nage district. He located the leak,\nbut at the same time another de\nveloped that loosed a swirling tor\nrent from Lake Pontchartrain. and\nhurled him against and between a\nset of pilings.\nThe diver was wearing a helmet,\nbut did not have on the usual div\ner's suit and instead of having his\nlifeline tied around his body, was\nholding it in his hand. The rush\ning water tore the line from his\ngrasp, and he was helpless except\nfor his contact with the upper\nworld by means of his air hose.\nOther divers assisting in the at\ntempted rescue, said that if an ef\nfort were made to pull Danese from\nbetween the pilings by the air hose,\nwater would rush Into his helmet.\nBuenos Aires Quiet\nAfter Street Riot\nBUENOS AIRES. Argentina. Sept\n9\u2014The streets of the capital\nwere cleared of gun brandishing\nmobs today, only after seven per\nsons had been killed. 56 wound*\u2019\nand pillage had ruled for several\nhours. The rioting was the after\nmath of a revolution which over\nthrew President Hipolito Irigoyen.\nThe disorders were precipitate!'\nby troops which mistook a minor\ndisturbance for a counter-revolu\ntion against General Jose Evarlsto\nUriburu and his ministry, who were\ninduced into office yesterday.\nThe city was calm on the surface\nfodav but there still were cases o'\nlooting In the armories by ounr\ncivilians who. having no arms, took\nvigorous steps to get them. Om\ncentral armory was ransacked and\n~et afire but there was no furthe\n'\u2022hooting reported after 2 a. m\n___\nIrigoyen Officials\nOrdered Arrested\nBUENOS AIRES. Sept. 9\u2014iTPt\u2014\nThe ministry of interior today ord\nered arrest of all senators, deputies\nand ministers under the Irigoyen\nregime, which was ended last Sat\nurday night by a successful re\nvolutionary movement.\nPresidents of all committees o'\nthe Personalista or Irigoyen branch\nof the radical party also were ord-1\nered detained.\nThe ministry issued the following\ncommunique:\n\u201cIn view of disturbances to th\ntranquility of the repubUc brough*\nabout by armed civilians, and since\nit is necessary to assure order and\nto make guarantees of life and\nproperty, let it be known that even\nperson hereafter found carrying\narms In public will be brought be\nfore a court martial.\u201d\nGeneral Augustin p. justo today\nwas designated Commandante Gen\nera! of the federal capital.\nVance Dies\nNEW YORK. Sept. 9.\nArthur Vance. 57. editor In chief of\nPictorial Review, died last night.\nHe had been ill for several weeks\nVance began newspaper work in\nBinehamton. N. Y.. later becom\ning editor of the Home Magazine.\nHe was editor of Woman\u2019s Home\nCompanion from 1900 to 1907.\n\n\u201cLet\u2019s Go Native\u2019\u2019\n1\\CK PA*1*\nStarting\nTomorrow\ni\nA\nNight\nWife-,\nMarried one night\nto a man who had\nnever seen her tn\ndaylight. To a man\nwho did not even\nknow she was his\nwife!\nThe fascinating\nstory of\n\u2018Anybody\u2019s\nWoman\u2019\n\u25a0tarring\nRuth\nChatterton\nand\nCLIVE BROOK\nA Paramount all\ntalking drama with\ncast featuring Paul\nLukas\n\u2014JS\nCity Briefs i\nj\nDickey's Old Reliable Eye Water\nrelives sun and wind burned eyes.\nAdv. (1)\nMail Late\u2014The airmail out of\nFort Worth, scheduled to arrive\nhere about 2 p. m., will be about\neight hours late Tuesday. Failure of\nthe Chicago-Dallas line to make I\nproper connections is given as the\nreason for the delay.\n__ I\nWork Progresses\u2014Work on the\n155,00 addition to the Cameron j\ncounty jail is progressing rapidly.\nThe new section is expected to be\nready for occupancy within the\nnext two months.\nFifty feet new guaranteed garden j\nhose, $4.45; water pipe, lumber,\ndoors, windows, at low prices. Sales\nCo., 3rd. and Fronton.\u2014Adv. 9.\nOn Visit.\u2014Miss Marla del Rosaria\nRamirez left Monday morning for\nVictoria, Tex., to visit relatives.\nIn Galveston Sheriff Frank\nBrown Is in Galveston attending\nthe state democratic convention.\nReturn.\u2014Mr. and Mrs. Gordon\nStreet returned to Brownsville early\nthis week from the north where j\nthey have been visiting relatives j\nMr. Street is president of the Rio I\nGrande Valley Trust Company.\nINTENTIONS FILED\nJose de la Luz Melendez and i\nCarolina Longoria. San Benito;\nFrederico Flores and Tomasita Na\nJar, Santa Marla; Hilario Fuente.<\nand Francisca Salinas. aL Paloma:\nSteve Pelaggl. Fort Brown, and j\nPaulina Shelden, Brownsville: Nlc-\nolas Castillon and Agustina Laura.\nCombes.\nBoy Is Writer Of\nSea Mystery Note\nST. PETERSBURG. Fla., Sept. 9.\n\u2014(/P)\u2014A boy with a taste for stories\nassumed responsibility today for a\nnote in a tin can found floating in\nthe water here Saturday that was\nbelieved to have been a distress\nmessage from the crew of the mys\ntry ship Commodore of Philadel\nphia, that disappeared thirty years\nago.\nCharles M. Raphun. Jr.. 11 years\nold, said that on Labor Day he\n'vnrote the note purporting to be\nfrom the wrecked ship Commodore,\nand sent it afloat in a can which\nhe found on the shores of Tampa\nBay. Charles said he got the name\nCommodore out of a library book,\nbut did not know that a ship of\nthat name was associated with a\nmystery of the sea.\nApril 6. 1901. the Commodore of\nPhiladelphia drifted into Brooklyn\nharbor without trace of a skipper\nor crew and no clue to their fate\nwas ever found.\nCapitol Theater Is\nBeing Remodelled\nPortionsof the exterior and the\ninterior of the Capitol theater are\nbeing remodeled and repainted in\nChinese red. according to manager\nJno. C. Fanning.\nThe new color is being adopted\nby the Publix chain, the local man,\nexplained.\nThe work will be completed this\nweek, having started Monday.\nCARD OF THANKS\nWe wish to thank our many\nfriends, especially members of the\nChristian Church, for the sympathv\nshown us and for the beautiful\nfloral offerings received during the\nsickness and death of our beloved\ndaughter. Juanita Catherine.\nMr. and Mrs. Frank Eans.\nDemos\u2019 Meeting\nSidelights\nCONTENTION HALL, Galveston\nSept. 9\u2014(<F)\u2014Governor Dan Moody\ndoes not know what he will do when\nhe vacates the chief executives of\nfice.\n\u2022T haven\u2019t the slightest notion\nwhat I will do or where I will go,\u2019 j\nhe replied to a question.\nA big event set for tonight is the\nwheelbarrow ride Senator Walter\nWoodul of Houston will give Georg*\nPurl of Dallas, noaiinee to succeed\nstate Senator Thomas B. Love from\nthat district. Purl and Woodul\nagreed that should Dallas count!\ngive Ross S. Sterling, gubernatorial\ncandidate, a larger majority that\nHarris county, the aspirant\u2019s home*\ncounty. Woodul would wheel Purl\ndown the beach and vice versa\nDallas county piled up a bigger\nlead than Harris county and Sen\nator Woodul is ready to carry out\nhis end of the bargain.\n\nValley Woman Near\nDeath in Hospital\n(Special to The Herald*\nRAYMONDVILLE. Sept. 9\u2014 Mrs.\nS. L. Gill received a telegram late\nMonday evening stating that Mrs.\nEddie Byrd Burton who recentlv j\nunderwent an operation in a San\nAntonio Hospital, was not expected\nto live through the night.\nMrs. Burton is one of the pioneer\nresidents of Raymondville. having!\nbeen a resident here for the past\nfifteen years. She is very prom\ninent in church and social affairs\nin Raymondville and for a number\nof years held the Ford Agency in\nthis city. 1\nOil Still Explodes\nAt Pt. Arthur Plant\nPORT ARTHUR. Sept. 9\u2014{*\u00bb\u2014\nExplosion of A high pressure oil\nstill at the Gulf -efinery\u2019a plant\nhere last night was estimated to\nday to have caused loss of ap\nproximately $16,600.\nThe explosion was believed to\nhave been caused by a bursting\npipe through which the crude oil\nwas flowing. Flames enveloped the\nentire still for about 30 minutes\nbefore the oil could be cut off and\nthe fire brought under contr?J^\nTHIS MAX\nended his\nheadaches\nthis quick\n\\way.\njCOR years be suffered with sick\nheadaches. Sometimes it was\nfrom over-work, sometimes\nnerves or his stomach, but when\nthe headaches came he suffered\nuntold misery.\nNow when headaches come he\ntakes Capudine and he gets relief\nin just a few minutes.\nBeing liquid,Capudine acts imme\ndiately, often in one-third the time\nrequired by other forms. It con\ntains no narcotics, does not disturb\ndigestion and is approved by doc\ntors and druggists. Even with the\nmost severe headache, relief comes\nvery quickly.\nSold at Drue Scores. 10*. 30* A 00* bottles\nand by the dose at sods fountains.\nHICKS 4*\nLapuatne\nW FOR HSAOACHSS\nJust as natural loveliness is pleasing to your eyes, the natural mildness\nof Camel Cigarettes is pleasing to your taste.\nCamel is an amazingly mild smoke. Yet it is never flat\u2014never taste\nless. All the mellow aroma of the choice tobaccos in the Camel blend is\npreserved and enhanced through every step of manufacture. There\u2019s no\nover-processing with its resultant insipidity no doctoring, for none is\nneeded.\nModern smokers have recognized the difference between mildness\nand flatness. They\u2019re swinging to Camels\u2014choosing a cigarette that\u2019s\nnaturally mild\u2014enjoying the real luxury of smoking.\nCamels\nC I\u00ab\u00bb It J ROToi*\nI\u00abUm Co., Wuuuu-SoIm* fcf.","height":"36728","width":"27604"}}
